05426nam a22007695i 9780823294855DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232948557 a10.1515/97808232948552doi  a(DE-B1597)577384  a(OCoLC)1263238342  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0200002bisacsh04a809.935812231 aWatson, Jini Kim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCold War Reckonings :bAuthoritarianism and the Genres of Decolonization /cJini Kim Watson. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b12 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Romanizations -- tIntroduction: Ruling Like a Foreigner: Theorizing "Free World" Authoritarianism in the Asia- Pacific Cold War -- tPart I. Authorities of Alignment, 1955-1988 -- tPart II. Genres of Cold War Reckoning, 1997-2017 -- tEpilogue: Authoritarian Lessons for Neoliberal Times -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aHow did the Cold War shape culture and political power in decolonizing countries and give rise to authoritarian regimes in the so-called free world? Cold War Reckonings tells a new story about the Cold War and the global shift from colonialism to independent nation-states. Assembling a body of transpacific cultural works that speak to this historical conjuncture, Jini Kim Watson reveals autocracy to be not a deficient form of liberal democracy, but rather the result of Cold War entanglements with decolonization.Focusing on East and Southeast Asia, the book scrutinizes cultural texts ranging from dissident poetry, fiction, and writers' conference proceedings of the Cold War period, to more recent literature, graphic novels, and films that retrospectively look back to these decades with a critical eye. Paying particular attention to anti-communist repression and state infrastructures of violence, the book provides a richaccount of several U.S.-allied Cold War regimes in the Asia Pacific, including the South Korean military dictatorship, Marcos' rule in the Philippines, illiberal Singapore under Lee Kuan Yew, and Suharto's Indonesia. Watson's book argues that the cultural forms and narrative techniques that emerged from the Cold War-decolonizing matrix offer new ways of comprehending these histories and connecting them to our present. The book advances our understanding of the global reverberations of the Cold War and its enduring influence on cultural and political formations in the Asia Pacific.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCold War in literature. 0aDecolonization in literature. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAnti-communism.  aAuthoritarianism.  aDecolonization.  aDevelopmental state.  aGlobal Cold war.  aIndonesian literature and film.  aPhilippine Literature.  aPostcolonial studies.  aSingaporean literature and film.  aSouth Korean literature and film.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z97